dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Stigma
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour exhibits or describes stigmatizing attitudes or behavior toward people who are infected, COVID-19 survivors, health workers, particular ethnic or racial groups (including both beliefs and discriminatory treatment)

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Characteristics of the virus
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to how the virus behaves (mutations, contagiousness, etc.)

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Status/end of the epidemic
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to the progress of the pandemic (infections, waves, etc.) or predicts the end of the pandemic

dataElements.name: RL- Belief: Certain medications can prevent or cure coronavirus
dataElements.shortName: Certain medications can prevent or cure
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour reflects the belief that medications, such as malaria medications or antiretrovirals or other approved or informal medications can prevent or cure coronavirus
dataElements.formName: Certain medications can prevent or cure coronavirus

dataElements.name: RL- Response: Rumour analyzed
dataElements.description: Use this code to document that the rumour has been coded and analyzed

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Conspiracy theory
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour describes a conspiracy theory (a theory that rejects official accounts of an event or situation in favor of secret organizations or secret plots)

dataElements.name: RL- Rumour
dataElements.description: Enter the rumour verbatim (word for word as it was first submitted)
dataElements.formName: Enter the rumour verbatim (word for word as it was first submitted)

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Estimates of case counts or deaths
dataElements.shortName: Estimates of case counts or deaths
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to perceptions of the accuracy of published case counts or deaths, or feelings about the number of cases or deaths
dataElements.formName: Estimates of case counts or deaths

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Origin of the illness
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to where the illness came from (animals, a laboratory, etc.)

dataElements.name: RL- Community correspondent code
dataElements.description: Enter the code of the community correspondent who submitted the rumour

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Access to resources (masks, medicines, finances)
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to individual, community, or national ability to access resources needed for COVID-19 prevention or treatment, or other resources as a result of the pandemic

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Signs and symptoms
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to the signs and symptoms of COVID-19

dataElements.name: RL- Belief: Self-medication or treating at home is better than going to a facility
dataElements.shortName: Self-medication or treating at home is better
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour reflects a preference for self-medication or home remedies for COVID-19
dataElements.formName: Self-medication or treating at home is better

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Gender
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to gender norms or experiences of men vs women during the pandemic

dataElements.name: RL- Source of rumour
dataElements.description: Describe who submitted the rumour or where the rumour was found. Do not try to trace it back to the source. If the rumour was mentioned by multiple sources, enter it multiple times.

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Confinement, quarantine, or lockdowns
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to lockdowns or quarantine procedures

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Mode of transmission
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to how the virus is transmitted between people

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Perceptions of who is at risk
dataElements.shortName: Perceptions of who is at risk
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to whether certain populations can become infected, or comparisons in the level of risk between different types of people. It may include age, ethnicity, gender, socioeconomic status, preexisting conditions, or other factors.
dataElements.formName: Perceptions of who is at risk

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Other
dataElements.description: Use this code if you would like to propose a new theme that is not captured above

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Prevention
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to prevention methods such as wearing masks, social distancing, reducing large gatherings, hand washing, or theories about other foods, drinks, or processes that may prevent COVID-19

dataElements.name: RL- Data entry agent code
dataElements.description: Enter your own code (the code of the person entering and coding the data)

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Traditional or religious medicine
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour describes theories about traditional or religious medicine as prevention or treatment for COVID-19, or describes the use of traditional or religious medicine in communities

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Treatment or cure
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to possible or actual treatments for COVID-19, or cures

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Suspect case or death
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to an actual suspected COVID-19 case or death. Do not enter names or locations of individuals, but refer the rumour to surveillance experts if warranted.

dataElements.name: RL- Belief: A coronavirus vaccine is being tested without our knowledge or against our will
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour reflects the belief that a vaccine against SARS-CoV-2 may be tested on an unwilling population (forcibly injected, required by the government, disguised as routine vaccinations, etc.)
dataElements.formName: A coronavirus vaccine is being tested without our knowledge or against our will

dataElements.name: RL- Analysis: Reflections and recommendations
dataElements.description: To allow for reflexivity, note any comments, reflections, or recommendations linked to this rumour
dataElements.formName: Note any comments, reflections, or recommendations that this rumour prompts

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Government response
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to the government response, including perceptions of the success of the response or specific feedback or assessment of motivations

dataElements.name: RL- Belief: Case counts are over or underestimated for political reasons
dataElements.shortName: Case counts over/underestimated for pol reasons
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour reflects the belief that official case counts cannot be trusted, that health officials are overestimating them for financial gain or underestimating them for political reasons, or that health workers are falsely diagnosing clients
dataElements.formName: Case counts are over or underestimated for political reasons

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Other (specify)
dataElements.description: In a few words, describe the new theme

dataElements.name: RL- Belief: Coronavirus does not exist
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour reflects the belief that coronavirus does not exist or is an invention

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Seeking care at health facilities for testing or treatment
dataElements.shortName: Seeking care for testing or treatment
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to the process of obtaining healthcare at general health facilities or COVID-19 testing or treatment centers
dataElements.formName: Seeking care at health facilities for testing or treatment

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Consequences of the pandemic (economic, social, etc)
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to the impact of the pandemic on economic or social aspects of daily life or communities, or other consequences of the pandemic.
dataElements.formName: Consequences of the pandemic (economic, social, etc)

dataElements.name: RL- Belief: Coronavirus only affects certain people
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour reflects the belief that

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Vaccination
dataElements.description: Use the code if the rumour relates to vaccinations, either for COVID-19 or routine vaccinations

dataElements.name: RL- Belief: Certain foods or drinks can prevent or cure coronavirus
dataElements.shortName: Certain foods/drinks can prevent or cure
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour reflects the belief that drinking alcohol or hot water or other beverages or eating certain foods can prevent or treat coronavirus
dataElements.formName: Certain foods or drinks can prevent or cure coronavirus

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Fear or perceived severity of the illness
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to how serious the illness is or a sense of fear or foreboding about the pandemic

dataElements.name: RL- Response: Flag for immediate review or referral
dataElements.description: Use this code only if the rumour may warrant immediate action from law enforcement or surveillance experts

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Contact tracing
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to the process of following up contacts of known cases

dataElements.name: RL- Type of rumour
dataElements.description: Check the box that best describes the type of rumour

dataElements.name: RL- Belief: Recommended measures (masks, distancing, etc.) do not work or are harmful
dataElements.shortName: Recommended measures do not work or are harmful
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour reflects skepticism about whether recommended prevention measures work to prevent the spread of COVID-19, or suspicions that the measures are actually harmful or spread COVID-19
dataElements.formName: Recommended measures (masks, distancing, etc.) do not work or are harmful

dataElements.name: RL- Theme: Denial of the illness
dataElements.description: Use this code if the rumour relates to whether or not coronavirus exists
